Binary entry point for `ctx-verify`; contains no verification logic itself — all real work is delegated to `ctx_verify::cli::run` and `ctx_verify::runner::ProcRunner`.

Handles `--contract` specially: checked via raw `std::env::args()` scan *before* `Cli::parse()` runs, so it bypasses clap entirely and prints `ctx_verify::cli::CONTRACT` then exits 0. Any new clap-level flag named `--contract` would be shadowed by this pre-check.

Exit code convention: `Ok(true)` → 0 (checks passed), `Ok(false)` → 1 (checks failed), `Err` → 2 (tool error, message written to stderr). Callers scripting around this binary rely on that three-way split.

All output goes through explicit writer handles (`stdout().lock()`, `stderr().lock()`), never `println!`/`eprintln!` — this is deliberate so `cli::run` can be tested by passing an in-memory writer instead of real stdout.

`emit` swallows write failures silently (empty `if result.is_err() {}`) — intentional, since if the output/error channel itself is broken there's no way to report that failure.